{{Citations needed|date=August 27, 2020}} {{How to reference|date=August 27, 2020}} {{Infobox person | name = Kunshin | native_name = 軍神 | native_name_lang= ja | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = Japanese | occupation = God of war | known_for = Worshipped in Japanese history as a deity of military success and valor }}
'''Kunshin''' (軍神) refers to:
# A [[god]] who governs [[military]] affairs and [[war]], often referred to as '''Bujin''' (武神) or '''Toshin''' (闘神). # A [[soldier]] who was [[deification|deified]] after a heroic [[death in battle]].
== Overview ==
'''Kunshin''' refers to a deity believed to bring victory in battle and to protect warriors. In [[Japan]], gods such as [[Takemikazuchi]] and [[Futsunushi]], who played roles in subduing [[Ashihara no Nakatsukuni]], were worshipped at [[Kashima Shrine]] and [[Katori Shrine]], respectively, as military gods. Additionally, the [[Great Deity of Suwa]] (諏訪大社の祭神), [[Takeminakata]], is also considered a god of war.
== Traditional War Deities == In Japan, the following deities are worshipped as war gods: * '''{{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕槌神}}''' ([[Kashima Shrine]]) * '''{{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主神}}''' ([[Katori Shrine]]) * '''{{ill|Takeminakata|ja|建御名方神}}''' ([[Suwa Grand Shrine]]) – Revered as "Japan's foremost war god." * '''{{ill|Okuninushi|ja|大国主}}''' ([[Izumo Taisha]]) * '''{{ill|Susanoo|ja|スサノオ}}''' * '''{{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|ヤマトタケル}}'''
== Japanese Middle and Early Modern Eras == During the [[Heian period]] and [[medieval Japan]], the [[Genji clan]] (源氏) worshipped the [[Hachiman deity]] (八幡神) as a clan deity, spreading its influence as a military god.
=== Resurrected War Gods === * '''{{ill|Kusunoki Masashige|ja|楠木正成}}''' * '''{{ill|Nitta Yoshisada|ja|新田義貞}}'''
=== Sengoku Period === * '''{{ill|Asakura Sōteki|ja|朝倉宗滴}}''' of [[Echizen Province]], renowned for his strategic prowess. * '''{{ill|Tachibana Dōsetsu|ja|立花道雪}}''' of [[Bungo Province]], famous as Kyushu's god of war. * '''{{ill|Uesugi Kenshin|ja|上杉謙信}}''' of [[Echigo Province]], often called the "war god" due to his devotion to [[Bishamonten]] and unmatched military skills.
== Modern Military Deities in Japan == From the [[Meiji era]] onward, soldiers who died bravely in combat, such as [[Nogi Maresuke]] and [[Tōgō Heihachirō]], were revered as military deities. Examples include:
=== Tamejirō Hirose === {{main|Hirose Tamejirō}} [[Hirose Tamejirō]], a [[naval officer]] known for his heroism during the [[Russo-Japanese War]].
=== Sōta Tachibana === {{main|Tachibana Sōta}} Renowned for his actions at the Battle of [[Liaoyang]].
=== Taketsuna Sasaki === {{main|Sasaki Taketsuna}} Famous for his role in the [[Mongol invasions of Japan]].
== References == <references />
== Related Articles == * {{ill|Military rituals|ja|勝軍治要祓}}
